<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-420  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 420.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  March 28 1990 n129 p23(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DVI sets pace for Windows 3.0 extensions. (developing softwaretools for Microsoft Windows 3.0) (digital video interactive)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Operating EnvironmentsSoftware DesignProgram Development ToolsDigital Video-InteractiveGraphical User InterfaceMultimedia Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DVI sets pace for Windows 3.0 extensions As Intel and IBM introduce theirfirst DVI products, more than a dozen software vendors joined Microsoft inannouncing future plans for multimedia development tools for Windows 3.0.andM;Microsoft, Autodesk and Micrografx are among the companies promising to bringout multi-media extensions to Windows before the end of the year.andP;  Microsoftsays it will work with the vendors to define data formats and identify toolswhich let developers create and manipulate applications that combine audio,photo-quality stills, motion video, and animation and text.andM;&quot;We plan to offer tools that enable you to put together presentations withmusic, slide shows and interactive video,&quot; Micrografx president GeorgeGrayson stated.andP;  He added that Micrografx is building a multi-media kernelthat will allow developers to write scripts for controlling presentations andmanufacturing processes.andP;  He was unable to give a firm release date for thekernel but said that some products are expected to arrive this year.andM;Autodesk, which launched an image processing program called Animator lastAugust, plans to port Animator's 'Player' facility to Windows 3.0 before theend of the year.andP;  This move would allow Animator presentations to be calledup from within Windows 3.0.andP;  However, the company says that it has &quot;nocommitment&quot; to port Autodesk Animator itself, to the Windows environment.andO;</TEXT></DOC>